rectory behavior or making assumptions that contradict your architecture.\n\nDespite the friction, your sessions show a productive core: 28 fully achieved outcomes, strong synthesis work (analyzing memory-block files into markdown), and moments you rated as \"essential\" — like when Claude traced false deacon-down alerts to a zsh tmux alias mangling return codes, or when it cleaned 68 over-generated Bitwarden files down to a minimal 3-file solution. You're building something genuinely novel with your **@-linking context navigation system and agent handoff patterns**, and you use Claude most effectively when the task is well-scoped (infrastructure debugging, file cleanup, research synthesis) rather than open-ended design where your vision and Claude's defaults clash.",
